A Republican Strategy to Hinder Obama’s Reelection
The Republican leaders justified their policy for the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers this last a myth and states that electoral fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die due to a lightning drop.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is true: these new provisions will negatively affect the rate of participation.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike what happens in Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And on that same line, a majority of American governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that made it difficult for the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Accordingly, 180 bills were introduced during 2011 that restricted the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, as well as an American citizenship test.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of the scrutiny, and withdraw their right to vote for citizens with criminal background.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to submit an identity document with photography.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
In 2008, the U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana law.
Therefore, the Republican authorities hurried to extend that practice to other states.
In recent years, the authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to submit an identity document with photography.
It is important to note that, unlike what happens in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as the Social Security Card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, i.e., 21 million people in the age of voting, do not have any identity documents with photographs issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
Thus, new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low income.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have an identity document with photography.
And there's even more.
In many states, students, voters who vote most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the identity document with photography issued by their institution.
On the other hand, those same states authorize members of the fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004 no state required the citizenship test to vote.
Arizona was the first state to present this requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws that require voters to demonstrate that they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly seeking to limit the Hispanic vote.
It seems that two in three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican legislators supported in 2011 certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of the election in eight states.
In addition, they restricted the right of people and groups to create a help service to voters who would like to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 resulted in the registration rate of new voters dropping in 2010 compared to 2006.
Furthermore, Republican legislators adopted laws in five other states that favored the reduction of the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 Florida elections, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while they represented only 13% of state voters.
In the case of the Hispanics, it was exactly the same.
These represent only 11% of voters, equivalent to 24% of citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, representing 76 percent of the electorate, represent only 46 percent of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have fervently opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
In this sense, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. prosecutor intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
In part, the damage could be limited.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law that required the presentation of an identity document with photography.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan character of the laws that have been voted, as it is clear that with them it is intended to influence the results of 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that have adopted such laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed at the electoral school to achieve the presidency.
It’s too early to affirm with certainty whether these legislative changes at the scale of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is true: these new provisions will negatively affect the rate of participation.
In this regard, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
