A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes contain in the public account book, which is spread throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched on computers and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege to add that complementary line.
It is a stage of piecing files, i.e., transformation of a large file into a shorter and single numerical footprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "twice" the assembly.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zero at first).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of assemblies of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, in order to commit a fraud, a user would like to pay twice with the same money very fast (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions as valid; the other would remain orphan, as both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
