Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency last week, Poland was accepted as a twelfth ESA member. It is the second ESA member country of the former Eastern Europe block, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began an intense collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the later years participated in the agency’s project commission.
However, the path of Poland towards the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already dedicated to flights to space before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory in which, on December 6, 1933, presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left indifferent attendees and, years later, Šternfeld reminded that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie Award and André Louis Hirsch for his "Introduction to the Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great driver of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known around the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when his name was put to one of the hidden face craters of the moon.
Already in 1925 a drain was built in Poland that would be provided with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is not known who was the author of the proposal and the details of the project are not known either.
It is unclear whether the rocket would be used for the start of the drain or for its braking.
The information about this drain is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
As of 1933, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to the missiles.
The research was funded by Komorka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslavem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the research came to the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 appeared in the specialized press the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by engineer Rohziński and the following year was published the studio "Rakieta - torpeda powietzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all projects of military missile techniques and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautic Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 edition of the magazine Problemy, for the first time it refers to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronomy.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotowicze proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautic Society (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Astronautic Federation.
He performed this charge until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA was significantly involved in the development of the RM probe (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was conducted.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and was first released on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had a peak of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was finished and in the summer of 1959 the air tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets began in the desert of Błędow.
The rocket was 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development was going to be a real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was going to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the height wind.
However, in 1962 the work was suspended.
The successor of the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built in 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which were differentiated by the space available for scientific apparatus.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the available space for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first air tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg to 60 km height.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 version were later built.
It is also necessary to mention the entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
In the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined the cosmic space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
