Last week the Constitutional Court suspended the law of social labour.
The resolution awakened a warm discussion in society.
It will certainly be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulatory.
Consequently, this means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and free and unlimited private capital movement, along with unfreeded financial speculation.
The effect of major differences on the labour cost (of wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept, it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, attempts to shorten distances and for that "leads to a drop" of the competitor's price with the aim of making the most of the market and thus increasing its margin of profit.
On a large scale means, for most entrepreneurs, moving production abroad, buying there cheaper or disappearing. The result is a high unemployment in those countries where the price of work, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, thereby, is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the social spending of the state necessarily grows.
This entire situation leads to the total disinterest of entrepreneurs in paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damage they have caused in their efforts to gain profits.
The situation is so universally known that it is not necessary to present specific statistical data.
Unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations in certain economies where governments of these countries are forced to compete with the objective of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thus attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own population without taking into account the social decline.
This is evident above all in the changes to existing laws.
The objective is to force the population to accept the dictatorship of private capital, especially in terms of wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the economic obligation system in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other hand, through the restricted employee rights in respect of labour rights.
The result is a growing poverty along with increased differences between poor and rich.
For a number of years, there are in Germany food delivery points for poor people that cannot be kept with their own work.
The number of people receiving this kind of aid is already a million.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, a fairly frequent case occurs: employees with such a low wage that the state must pay the rest to reach the necessary minimum to survive.
A scandal of this type related to the situation of the German federal parliament’s auxiliary employees was published.
The savings of almost all southern EU states lead, without a doubt, to the same situation. People, pressed by an abismal decline in their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to malfunction with a bad wage at the border of society, with the hope that someday they will reach the private investor country.
Do you need to ask where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never comes, since Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turkish, Moroccan, Egyptian or Africans continue to work for a small part of a European wage.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media state to the saciety that the state should not contribute capital to the economy, which leads to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by entering into control.
Then, it is necessary to wonder whether private capital does not influence its selfishness in the political march and, therefore, throughout the state.
In this case, the answer is clearly affirmative.
The test is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the field of corruption, in mutual favours, in a legislation that is virtually reprobable everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany the situation is as follows: state ministries, in the absence of financial means, commission the drafting of laws to private legal companies, which are often linked to the industry.
These types of bills are later passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not emanate from the people, as it is announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups representing their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation are quickly in a situation like that describing Appians in his work The crisis of the Roman republic in the times of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state had long disintegrated and the administrations were dealing with force."
In exchange for bribes, illegitimately obtained favors and help to finance stones or swords.
The bribery and corruption spread without any impediment and the people went to the urns with the vote opened in advance... "There were no people with character aspired to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was eight months without consules..."
The conclusion, as in ancient times, is that today’s society is based on unconsidered preferences of individual benefit without taking into account the common interests.
Private capital is not able, in its essence, to understand and claim the benefits of the whole society.
The result is the same as that of then, a decline of the unprecedented elite, without an effort to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be seen in the unfreeded liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a defined pause, in waiting for the next coup.
The truly demolishing fact is that the current elite completely ignores the losses of hundreds of thousands of lives, social and humanitarian disasters of which we have been witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and most recent history.
The suspension of the law on public procurement is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the Czech Republic government will be forced to continue searching for other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution goes through concrete socio-political reforms, which reinforce both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of state.
