And that’s like one day, in a Frisian farm, we covered the appropriate by-product from agriculture.
For many years, a plastic fabric of scarce millimeters thickness is used in greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands as a basis for holding the roots of crops.
This is a cheap and efficient material.
This thin tissue lasts two seasons and then removes.
For the library, this fabric was first pressed in such amounts until it achieved four-inch thick irons.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells to a mixture of new car and sports shoes.
