However, they play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the United States by refraining from voting in important decisions such as in the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, German posture enjoys a huge degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not think there has been such a drastic breakdown as in Libya.
Perhaps Germany has achieved a certain respect.
Ultimately, all of this has not done but demonstrate that it is a country that they take seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
Instead, the US has clearly shown itself in favour of a veto.
Is there a difference in opinions between the United States and many European nations?
These differences have always existed due to US internal policy.
I think Obama’s government secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
